## Context

This surface carries a specific risk inherited from the root spec's
scope-creep tripwires but realized locally: landing pages accumulate
feature tiles, social proof, newsletter captures, and pricing teasers
because each addition feels individually harmless. This spec makes each
forbidden addition specifically out of scope so the implementor can
refuse them by citing this file. The risk is not writing a bad landing —
it is writing a landing that looks acceptable in isolation but has
quietly grown into a generic marketing page that pattern-matches as
such.

This spec narrows the root to the landing surface's unique responsibility:
the sequenced beats that deliver a visitor to the install block with
enough context to paste without second-guessing.

## Strategy

**Vertical single-column, no sidebar.** Engineers scan top-to-bottom;
side columns are filtered as chrome. The single-column rule also forces
every section to earn its full-width slot — there is no "put it in the
sidebar" escape hatch for content that does not justify a beat.

**Five beats in this order, no more, no less:**

1. **Install-as-hero.** Headline, one-line subhead, MCP config JSON block
   with copy button, three-step numbered sequence (paste, restart,
   `aide_init`), a small troubleshooting callout naming the common
   friction modes. This IS the hero. No separate hero-above-install.
2. **Cost-of-not-knowing strip.** A concrete, sourced dollar figure —
   a six-month fractional specialist engagement at $30K–$60K — with
   inline source attribution. Anchors the business case: domain
   knowledge has historically been expensive to acquire, and AIDEMD
   makes it free to capture and cascade. No specific regulated-domain
   specialties named; the figure is the universal anchor.
3. **How it works.** The pipeline shows eight named agents — spec-writer,
   domain expert, strategist, architect, implementor, QA, aligner,
   auditor — as vertical nodes with one-sentence annotations per node.
   The brain is shown as shared infrastructure accessed by four agents
   (domain expert writes, strategist reads, architect reads the coding
   playbook and brain, auditor reads the coding playbook and brain)
   rather than as a pipeline stage. The fix loop (QA produces todo,
   implementor fixes one item per session in clean context, QA
   re-validates) and resume-mid-pipeline (orchestrator detects state
   from file existence and picks up where the last session left off) are
   visible as mechanism annotations, not hidden. This is the mechanism
   section; it is where the methodology framing ("intent is the
   contract, code is ephemeral") lives, not the hero.
4. **vs rules packs.** Dedicated section naming CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md,
   and .cursorrules as the nearest-neighbor category and describing the
   specific mechanical differences. Available ammunition beyond the core
   persistence-gap argument: auto-learning (when the fix loop closes,
   retro findings promote to the brain at `process/retro/` — rules packs
   cannot learn from their own failures), misalignment tags (QA traces
   where intent was lost to a specific pipeline stage — rules packs
   cannot diagnose drift), upgrade command (AIDEMD versions its methodology
   artifacts and updates them in place — rules packs do not version),
   coding playbook (the architect navigates a structured convention
   hierarchy via a dedicated skill — rules packs are flat unstructured
   text). The architect picks which differentiators fit the sixty-second
   reading budget; the spec provides all of them as available ammunition.
   This section closes the most likely confusion the audience brings in.
5. **Hallucination evidence.** Stanford HAI / Dahl et al., 2024,
   attributed verbatim: "purpose-built legal AI still hallucinates on
   over one in six queries." Cited as evidence against other tools'
   approach, never as evidence of AIDE's own track record.
6. **Final install block.** Identical to the hero's install block.
   Safety-net CTA for visitors who scrolled past the first one. (Count
   this as beat 6 if you like; it is the hero repeated, not a new
   beat's worth of content.)

The numbering here is not negotiable; adding a sixth content beat between
"how it works" and "vs rules packs" or between the hallucination
callout and the final CTA opens a scope-creep door this spec holds
closed. The implementor refuses additions by pointing at this list.

**Not every new mechanism needs LP copy.** This spec provides ammunition;
the architect picks what fits the reading budget. The eight agents,
Obsidian brain, and auto-learning are the headline features. Misalignment
tags, resume-mid-pipeline, and upgrade are supporting mechanisms that
strengthen beats 3 and 4 if space allows.

**No persistent top navigation.** A header with "Docs / Pricing / Blog"
gives the visitor three ways to leave the conversion path before they
reach the install block. The landing has no header. Docs are a single
footer link, deliberately below the final install CTA so docs are the
after-install reference, not the before-install distraction.

**Copy is hedge-free, short, declarative, verb-first.** No "helps you,"
no "empowers teams to," no "unlock the power of," no "AI-native." These
phrases survive draft review because they sound like something, but
engineers skim past them as noise and whatever survives is the short
strong sentences anyway. The landing's copy budget is spent on concrete
claims with sourced attribution, not on hedges.

**Hero leads with cascading intent and accessibility.** The hero
speaks to both audiences — non-technical users who describe what they
want, and technical builders who research an unfamiliar domain and let
AIDEMD cascade that knowledge into code. The headline names the mechanism
(intent in, working code out); the subhead names the eight-agent
pipeline and the brain as the persistence layer. The methodology
framing ("intent is the contract, code is ephemeral") lives in beat 3,
the how-it-works section, not in the hero. Two hero copy variants are
acceptable for launch and the implementor picks between them at build
time; both are documented in the Good Examples section below.

**Cost strip ships one anchor figure.** The research note has four
defensible specialist rate ranges, but naming specific regulated-domain
specialties (tax attorneys, physician advisors) positions AIDEMD against
domains we explicitly avoid. The strip ships a single universal anchor
— the six-month fractional engagement total ($30K–$60K) — which
communicates "domain knowledge is expensive to acquire" without naming
a specialty that implies AIDEMD replaces licensed professionals.

**Domain examples are operational, not regulated — enforced locally.**
Every section on this surface must comply with the root spec's
operational-not-regulated rule. No legal, medical, tax, or compliance
domains named as AIDEMD use cases. The cost strip names the cost of
acquiring domain knowledge generically, not the cost of a specific
licensed professional. The how-it-works section describes what the AIDEMD
pipeline does, not what users have built. The domain-expert annotation
names operational domains (internal tools, content production) not
regulated ones. The hallucination callout cites other tools' failures
as evidence that even purpose-built AI gets domains wrong — reinforcing
why AIDE's approach (persistent, auditable research) matters, not
implying AIDEMD solves those regulated domains. No testimonials, no case
studies, no "built with AIDEMD" badges, no founder quotes.

## Good examples

**Hero copy variants (implementor picks one at build time):**

Variant A (accessibility-first):
> **Describe what you want. AIDEMD cascades your intent into working code.**
>
> Eight specialized agents — spec-writer, domain expert, strategist,
> architect, implementor, QA, aligner, auditor — turn what you know
> into what you ship. Research persists to a brain every agent reads.
> Works with Claude Code today.
>
> `[paste this into .mcp.json]`  `[then run aide_init]`

Variant B (methodology-first):
> **Tell your agents what to build, not how to build it.**
>
> AIDEMD captures intent as a spec and cascades it through eight
> specialized agents. Domain knowledge persists to a brain — not a
> chat window — so every session starts where the last one left off.
>
> `[paste this into .mcp.json]`  `[then run aide_init]`

**Cost-of-not-knowing strip copy (ship verbatim, cite inline):**

> A six-month fractional specialist engagement runs $30,000–$60,000
> at the low end (Geisheker Group, 2026). AIDEMD captures the same
> domain knowledge for free via `npx`.

**Reading experience end-to-end:**

A visitor lands at 2:14pm. Fold one: hero — one headline, one subhead,
the JSON code block with a copy button, the three-step sequence, a
small troubleshooting callout. Fold two: the cost strip above. Fold
three: the how-it-works diagram with eight agent nodes (spec-writer,
domain expert, strategist, architect, implementor, QA, aligner, auditor)
shown as a vertical pipeline with the brain as shared infrastructure,
plus one-line annotations per node. Fold four: the vs-rules-packs section naming
CLAUDE.md/AGENTS.md/.cursorrules and the persistence-gap argument.
Fold five: the Stanford HAI callout with full attribution — framed as
evidence that even purpose-built domain AI gets it wrong, reinforcing
why persistent auditable research matters. Fold six: the final install
block, identical to the hero. Footer: one link, "Read the canonical
spec →" pointing to /docs. Total reading time about sixty seconds,
install completable in under two minutes, visitor never encounters a
form.

**Meta description direction:** The meta description and og:description
must convey cascading intent and accessibility — anyone can describe
what they want and AIDEMD turns it into working code through eight
specialized agents and a persistent brain. Do not reference "collapses
the specialist hire," regulated domains, multi-framework support, or
deprecated concepts like "byte-faithful" or "timestamped context." The
architect writes the exact copy; this spec provides the constraints.

## Bad examples

A hero that reads "The AI-native engineering workflow for modern
teams. Unlock agent productivity with AIDE. [Request early access]"
above an auto-playing demo video. Below it: a three-column feature
grid (Fast / Reliable / Open) with stock icons, a "Trusted by" logo
strip, a testimonials carousel with italic pull-quotes, a newsletter
signup card above the fold, a pricing teaser ("Free for open source /
$49/mo / Contact sales for Enterprise"), a "Meet the founders" block,
a FAQ accordion, a case-studies block describing "legal and medical
apps built with AIDEMD" (zero of which exist), and finally the install
block at the bottom of the page, hidden behind an email-capture form
and requiring a second click to reveal the actual command. A persistent
top nav offers "Docs / Blog / Pricing / About / Sign in," five
competing off-ramps. A visitor cannot tell in ten seconds whether AIDEMD
is a framework, a hosted product, a consultancy, or a newsletter, and
the install block is effectively unreachable within the first minute
of the visit.

A subtler failure mode: the five beats are present in the correct order,
but a sixth beat ("Built for teams like yours") has been inserted
between beats 3 and 4 with three testimonial pull-quotes. The page
still converts reasonably, but the testimonials are invented ("We
shipped our compliance app in two weeks!" — Alex, Fake Co.) because no
real users exist yet. The spec catches this specifically: testimonials
are in `outcomes.undesired` at the root level, and this surface spec
restricts the beat count to five to prevent the slot from existing in
the first place.

A subtler failure mode still: a hero that reads "AIDE collapses the
specialist hire into the agent loop" with a researcher annotation
listing "legal, clinical, tax, compliance" as example domains. This
positions AIDEMD against exactly the domains where a technical reader
would never trust it — nobody ships a legal or medical product on an
AI methodology they installed five minutes ago. The framing also
excludes non-technical users entirely by speaking only to engineering
teams replacing headcount. The correct hero names what AIDEMD actually
does (captures intent, cascades it into code) and speaks to anyone
who can describe what they want, not just engineers replacing
specialists they can't afford.

The subtlest failure mode: a how-it-works diagram that shows four
generic nodes ("Research -> Brain -> Intent -> Agents") instead of
naming the eight specific agents. This makes AIDEMD look like any
multi-agent framework rather than a pipeline with named, specialized
roles. The spec's intent paragraph specifically requires showing "eight
specialized agents as a concrete pipeline -- not generic AI agents." A
four-node diagram violates this by collapsing eight distinct roles into a
single "Agents" box, erasing the pipeline specificity that differentiates
AIDE from LangGraph, CrewAI, or any other multi-agent framework. The
correct diagram names all eight agents as vertical nodes and shows the
brain as shared infrastructure beside the pipeline, not as a pipeline
stage.

